{{Infobox language |name=Bozal Spanish |nativename=español bozal |states= The Americas |extinct= 1850 |familycolor=creole |family=[[Spanish-based creole languages|Spanish-based creole]]? |iso3=none |glotto=none }} '''Bozal Spanish''' is a possible extinct [[Spanish-based creole languages|Spanish-based creole language]] or [[pidgin]] that may have been a mixture of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Kikongo]], with [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] influences.<ref name="clements"/> Attestation is insufficient to indicate whether Bozal Spanish was ever a single, coherent or stable language, or if the term merely referred to any idiolect of Spanish that included African elements.
The Spanish distinguished ''[[black ladino|negros ladinos]]''<ref name="DRAE ladino">''[http://dle.rae.es/?id=GElf0MV esclavo ladino]'' in the [[Diccionario de la Real Academia Española]].</ref> ("Latinate Negros", those who spent more than a year in a Spanish-speaking territory) and ''negros bosales'' (wild, untamed<ref>{{citation | entry=bozal | editor1=[[Mario Andrew Pei]] | editor2=Salvatore Ramondino | title=The New World Spanish/English English/Spanish Dictionary | page=92 | publisher=[[New American Library]] | year=1968}}</ref> Negroes; those born in or freshly arrived from Africa).<ref>{{citation | author=Estéban Pichardo y Tapia | entry=BOZAL | title=Diccionario provincial de voces cubanas | page=39 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yWsVAAAAYAAJ | year=1836}}</ref> Similarly, the Portuguese distinguished between {{lang|pt|índios mansos}} (tamed, domesticated [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indians]]) and {{lang|pt|índios bravos}} (untamed, wild Indians), and between {{lang|pt|negros crioulos}} or {{lang|pt|ladinos}} (blacks born in the territory of a European empire, cf. Spanish [[Criollo people|criollo]] meaning natively-born white person from the colony; {{lang|pt|crioulo}} is now the main anti-black slur in [[Brazilian Portuguese]]) and {{lang|pt|negros africanos}} or {{lang|pt|boçais}} (blacks born in Africa).
Bozal Spanish was spoken by [[Atlantic slave trade|African slaves]] in [[Cuba]]<ref name="clements">Clements, J. Clancy. [http://ebooks.cambridge.org/chapter.jsf?bid=CBO9780511576171&cid=CBO9780511576171A014 "Bozal Spanish of Cuba"], ''The Linguistic Legacy of Spanish and Portuguese'', Cambridge University Press, 2009. 9780511576171</ref>, [[Uruguay]]<ref>http://www.geocities.ws/uruguayoculto/musica/tangooriental.html</ref> and other areas of [[South America|South]] and [[Central America]] from the 17th century up until its possible extinction at around 1850.<ref name="lipski">Lipski, John M. [http://benjamins.com/#catalog/books/impact.22.26lip/details "Where and how does bozal Spanish survive?"], ''Spanish in Contact: Policy, Social and Linguistic Inquiries'', John Benjamins Publishing Co., 2007.</ref> Although Bozal Spanish is extinct as a language, its influence still exists.<ref name="lipski"/> In some Cuban folk religious rituals today, people speak what they call "Bozal".<ref>Wirtz, Kristina. 2014. ''Performing Afro-Cuba: Image, Voice, Spectacle in the Making of Race and History''. [See Chapter 4.] Chicago: University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|978-0-226-11905-2}}</ref> Similarly, many songs of the [[afro (genre)|afro]] genre, which flourished in Cuba in the 1930s and '40s, contain lyrics reminiscent of the language.
