'''Hirawanu Tapu''' (c.1824&ndash;1900) was a notable New Zealand [[Moriori people|Moriori]] leader. He was born in [[Te Awapatiki]], [[Chatham Islands]], New Zealand.<ref name="DNZB Tapu">{{DNZB|King|Michael|1t12|Hirawanu Tapu|23 April 2017||Michael King}}</ref> He was a major source for [[Alexander Shand (ethnologist)|Alexander Shand]]'s works on Moriori history, traditions, chants and [[Moriori language|vocabulary]], and about 90 percent of all extant knowledge of his people's culture and language passed through his hands.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Shand |first=Alexander |date=December 1894 |title= The Moriori people of the Chatham Islands: their traditions and history |url=http://www.jps.auckland.ac.nz/document//Volume_3_1894/Volume_3,_No.4,_December_1894/The_Moriori_people_of_the_Chatham_Islands%3A_their_traditions_and_history%3A_Chapter_3,_Manaii_%28or_Manaia%29,_Kahukaka_and_Porotehiti_%28translation%29,_by_Alexander_Shand,_p187-198 |journal=Journal of the Polynesian Society |publisher= |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=187–198 |doi= |accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>

