==History==
{{see also|Mapuche history}}
When the Spanish arrived in Chile, they found four groups of Mapuche speakers in the region of [[Araucanía (historic region)|Araucanía]], from which the Spanish called them ''araucanos'': the [[Picunche people]] (from ''{{lang|arn|pikum}}'' 'north' and ''{{lang|arn|che}}'' 'people'), the [[Huilliche people]] (from ''{{lang|arn|willi}}'' 'south'), the [[Pehuenche people]] (from ''{{lang|arn|pewen}}'' 'monkey puzzle tree' ''[[Araucaria araucana]]''), and the [[Moluche people]]  (from ''{{lang|arn|molu}}'' 'west'). The Picunche were conquered quite rapidly by the Spanish, whereas the Huilliche were not assimilated until the 18th century. 

Mapudungun was the only language spoken in central Chile. The sociolinguistic situation of the Mapuche has changed rapidly. Now, nearly all of Mapuche people are bilingual or monolingual in Spanish. The degree of bilingualism depends on the community, participation in Chilean society, and the individual's choice towards the traditional or modern/urban way of life.<ref name= book>Gruyter, Mouton. A Grammar of Mapuche. Berlin: Walter de Gruyter GmbH and Co., 2008. Print.</ref>

There is some lexical influence from the [[Quechuan languages]] (''pataka'' 'hundred', ''warangka'' 'thousand') and more recently from Spanish.

==Dialects==
{{cladogram|title=Dialect sub-groups
