[[Linguist]] Robert A. Croese divides Mapudungun into eight dialectal sub-groups (I-VIII). Sub-group I is centered in [[Arauco Province]], Sub-group II is the dialect of [[Angol]], [[Los Ángeles, Bío Bío|Los Ángeles]] and the middle and lower [[Bío Bío River]]. Sub-group III is centered around [[Purén]]. In the areas around [[Lonquimay]], [[Melipeuco]] and [[Allipén River]] dialect sub-group IV is spoken. Sub-group V is spoken at the coast of [[Araucanía Region]] including [[Queule]], [[Budi Lake]] and [[Toltén]]. 

Temuco is the epicenter of the Mapuche territory today.<ref>(Smeets, Ineke (2008). A Grammar of Mapuche. Mouton de Gruyter.) </ref> Around [[Temuco]], [[Freire, Chile|Freire]] and [[Gorbea, Chile|Gorbea]] the sub-group VI is spoken. Group VII is spoken in [[Valdivia Province]] plus [[Pucón]] and [[Curarrehue]]. The last "dialect" sub-group is VIII which is the [[Huilliche language]] spoken from [[Ranco Lake|Lago Ranco]] and [[Bueno River|Río Bueno]] to the south and is not mutually intelligible with the other dialects.<ref name=Croese1985>{{cite book |last=Croese |first=Robert A.|editor1-last=Manelis Klein |editor1-first=Harriet|editor2-last=Stark|editor2-first=Louisa R.|date=1985 |title=South American Indian Languages: Retrospect and Prospect |chapter=21. Mapuche Dialect Survey|url= |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=University of Texas Press |pages=784–801 |isbn=0-292-77592-X}}</ref>

These can be grouped in four dialect groups: north, central, south-central and south. These are further divided into eight sub-groups: I and II (northern), III–IV (central), V-VII (south-central) and VIII (southern). The sub-groups III-VII are more closely related to each other than they are to I-II and VIII. Croese finds these relationships as consistent, but not proof, with the theory of [[Mapuche history#Origins|origin of the Mapuche]] proposed by [[Ricardo E. Latcham]].<ref name=Croese1985/>

The Mapudungun spoken in the Argentinean provinces of Neuquen and Rio Negro is similar to that of the central dialect group in Chile, while the Ranquel (Ranku ̈lche) variety spoken in the Argentinean province of La Pampa is closer to the northern dialect group.{{sfnp|Sadowsky|Painequeo|Salamanca|Avelino|2013|p=87}}

==Phonology==
{{IPA notice}}
===Prosody===
Mapudungun has partially predictable, non-contrastive stress. The stressed syllable is generally the last one if it is closed (''{{lang|arn|awkán}}'' 'game', ''{{lang|arn|tralkán}}'' 'thunder'), and the one before last if the last one is open (''{{lang|arn|rúka}}'' 'house', ''{{lang|arn|lóngko}}'' 'head'). There is no phonemic tone.

